title: For Sale:  GSG 522
postcontent:
JUST IN TIME FOR CHRISTMAS The American Tactical Imports GSG 522 Semi Auto Carbine is a great gun to plink and target shoot with. This rifle is chambered in .22 Long Rifle and has a 16.25" barrel. The magazine holds 22 rounds of ammunition, and the rifle has a retractable stock. This firearm comes in a black finish. Comes with additional stock,3- 22round GSG magazines. 
Specifications and Features: American Tactical Imports GSG 522 Semi Auto Carbine .22 Long Rifle 16.25" Barrel 22 Rounds Retractable Stock Textured pistol grip Intergrated weaver rail 33.6" overall length Black Finish 

I will sell the gun and 3 mags the stocks the lockable case and the CP Tactical Red/Green Dot Scope. All for the $475 

RATINGS (out of five stars) Style * * * * It’s hard to beat the looks of an MP5. I’m going to take a point away simply because ATI added weird looking dots on the pistol grip and equally unnecessary horizontal lines on the trigger group. My understanding was that these cosmetic changes were made in order to get to get Heckler & Koch to drop its lawsuit against GSG. If the non-authentic look really bugs you, you can shell out $50 for the retrofit kit. The fake suppressor looks cool, but be prepared for guys to approach you at the range asking about your can: they get a disappointed look on their face when you tell them it’s just a barrel shroud. 

Ergonomics * * * * * Feels like a slightly lighter version of a real-deal MP5. The safety, charging handle, and mag release are in the right positions. The weight and balance are comfortable. What’s not to love? 

Reliability * * * * 1/2 The GSG 522 experienced a few hiccups running through the first few mags, but then ran smooth as silk. On the last two range days of the testing, we put roughly 1200 rounds downrange with only one cleaning and only experienced one malfunction (and even that may have been ammo related). 

Customize This * * * * While this ain’t no Ruger 10-22, there’s a fair amount of factory “tacticool” that you can buy for the GSG 522 including dual mag clamps, flashlight holders, folding stocks, high and low scope mounts, laser mounts, etc. From the internet lore I’ve read, it seems that some of the stuff made by various air soft manufacturers will fit as well, but I can’t vouch for that. 

Accuracy * * * * 

The GSG is not quite as accurate as a bolt-action Anschutz or a CZ 452, but it’s going to embarrass your stock Ruger 10/22. Overall * * * * 1/2 The GSG 522 is a lot of fun if you are looking for a low-cost range plinker with the added benefit of sexy looks and historic provenance.

title: For Sale:  Swedish Mauser M96/38 CG   6.5 x 55 mm for sale
location: Northwest Milwaukee area, Wisconsin, United States
postcontent:
For sale is a Swedish Mauser, caliber 6.5 x 55, bolt action.  This is the M96/38, a model 96 that was retooled by the Swedish military to shorten the barrel to more of a carbine length to reflect the need their military had for more maneuverable (and lighter...) rifles for their ground troops.
Barrel is 24 inches long where the M96 was just a  hair over 29 inches in length.

The bore on this is rated a "1" which means their armorers thought it was in great condition, not as new, but pretty close.  The nominal bore diameter was 6.50 mm, nice tight fit giving good contact between the bullets surface and the lands/grooves in the barrel.  If you've read anything about these  you know they're known for their accuracy and their dependability.  Added bonus, they have great stopping power (these were/are caliber of choice for a lot of folks from anything from deer up to moose).  Accuracy with iron sights is fantastic, ask any number of board members here who shoot these, the rifle is typically more inherently accurate than the shooter...  I know that's true for me.

Now to the issue of "which numbers match"?  Easy, the only number I can find that does not match is the butt plate.  Yeah, I know, the butt plate.  The receiver, all parts of the bolt, the magazine floor plate, EVEN the front and rear barrel bands on this specimen match.  That, to be honest, is quite unusual given that refitting of important but incidental parts didn't focus on or worry about matching numbers.

title: For Sale:  Colt ombat Commander .45 ACP
postcontent: Way back around 1993 or so, I had a copy of American Handgunner magazine and saw two pistols on the cover. They were custom builds by a company I hadn't heard of previously, Evolution Gun Works, (EGW) in Doylestown, PA. One was a race gun and the other was a really good looking tactical piece. Doylestown wasn't all that far away at that time, so I took a Combat Commander that I recently acquired to them along with that copy of American Hangunner, and asked them to recreate the same work on my pistol. It took a few months but was worth the wait. I then put 50 rounds through it without a hitch and put it away and haven't fired it since. Lots of really good metalwork and machining went into Way back around 1993 or so, I had a copy of American Handgunner magazine and saw two pistols on the cover. They were custom builds by a company I hadn't heard of previously, Evolution Gun Works, (EGW) in Doylestown, PA. One was a race gun and the other was a really good looking tactical piece. Doylestown wasn't all that far away at that time, so I took a Combat Commander that I recently acquired to them along with that copy of American Hangunner, and asked them to recreate the same work on my pistol. It took a few months but was worth the wait. I then put 50 rounds through it without a hitch and put it away and haven't fired it since. Lots of really good metalwork and machining went into this, as can be seen in the pictures. 20 LPI on the front strap. Stippling around the base of the trigger guard. 30 LPI on the bottom and front of the trigger guard. Flat topped and serrated the slide. Lowered ejection port with rollover groove. Dovetailed front patridge type sight. Beautifully executed adjustible Bo-Mar rear sight. Serrations on back of rear sight, slide and extractor. Perfectly machined high swept beavertail which matches the S&A mainspring housing, extended thumb safety, and barrel bushing. Extended mag release button. Matte finish on the frame and top of the slide with a satin polish on the sides. Ultralight carbon trigger. One piece guide rod. Original Colt barrel. Great looking double diamond wood (Cocobolo?) grips. Etc. etc. I still have the build sheet and will send it along when I find it. Remodeling the house at present so nothing is where it used to be. I remember that the total for all of the work they did on this came to around $1200 (and that was in 1993 dollars). When you consider what you'd spend for that work today, this pistol is a bargain. I'm not a dealer so ask yours if he'll accept a shipment from a private seller. I can go through a dealer here if needed. Shipping and insurance is included in the sale price. Email me with any questions not answered in the pictures or text. Not interested in trades because this remodel project has gone way over budget, otherwise I wouldn't be parting with this.

postcontent:
I have a variety of indoor range brass for sale.  They have been fired and still have the primers.  You will need to clean and deprime them yourself.  I try to pick out pieces that are Berdan primed or are bent to the point that they cannot be reloaded.  However, some of these may get into the bags.  I add an extra 10 pieces for every 500 to ensure you have quality pieces.  I hand count each bag and get rid of any aluminum or steel casings.  They are all brass or nickel coated brass! These are mixed headstamp and the .45s have not been sorted for primer size.  These can be fixed with a cheap pocket reamer.   You will find a lot of Lake City and Remington in .223 as well as a 5.56 once in a while.  In the pistol cartridges, the majority are blazers, remingtons, winchesters, and federals.  There are also the military rounds (less than 1% of the rounds), aguila, hornady, cor-bon, and speer to name a few.

postcontent:
Standard features

All variations of the pistol include ambidextrous decocking levers and a reversible magazine release, as well as an integrated tactical accessory rail. In addition, the FNP-45 offers an ambidextrous slide release.

According to FNH USA, the FNP line of pistols is the only polymer-framed autoloading pistol on the market (as of its introduction) with fully replaceable frame rails; this allows the pistol to be rebuilt after extensive firing, thereby extending service life.[6] (Steyr M Series pistols also have this feature, and were released in 1999.)
Design and operation

The FNP series weapons are hammer fired weapons utilizing a Browning cam system with an external extractor. The trigger module is housed inside the polymer frame as an individual unit connected to the hammer. The magazine release button is held in place by a retention pin which can be removed to allow the magazine release button to be reversed. The trigger pull for the FNP-9 variant is generally 8 pounds while in double action and 3–4 pounds while in single action. While the lower frame is made of high-strength polymer, the slide is made of stainless steel. Generous magazine wells make reloading the weapon easy.

I also have extra FNH magazines and two kydex holsters, on for the pistol, one for 2 magazines.  Gun has custom stippling as well.

title: For Sale/Trade:  !!!!!!UPDATE!!!!!!!!.......ITHACA FLUES FIELD GRADE SXS 12GA. "COACHED"
postcontent: I have for sale or trade an Ithaca Flues hammerless double barrel shotgun made in Ithaca, NY in 1922.  Designed by Emile Flues.  I have contacted the former 28yr. lead gunsmith for Ithaca Gun Co. to inquire about a crack in the barrel.  I have a pic of the crack from a before picture if you need to see it.   After Ithaca was sold off he started his own gunsmithing right in Ithaca, NY, it is called Diamond Gunsmithing (www.diamondgunsmithing.com).  He specializes in vintage firearms restoration and repair.  The short and sweet of it is that my gun had a crack about 7"-8" from the choke, on the side of the barrel.  He advised me that is was not repairable, but he may have barrels to replace them but it requires custom smithing that I was not financially prepared for.  I opted to "coach" the gun and cut the barrel to 20".  It is perfectly legal under the 18/26 rule.  I also reblued the barrels.  I know how much value was lost in this procedure but it was lost when the crack happened before I got it.  I also didn't want to break up a numbers matching set.  All numbers match.  It has a different buttplate on it than it should.  It says "Winchester Repeating Arms Co."   This is a nice quick take down shotgun, literally 3 steps!  With the barrels shortened it will pack nicely into your gear.  I can negotiate on the price and I only sell face to face. I will not ship, sorry.
